** Neil Gaiman on Why We Read and What Books Do for the Human Experience (=
https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/08/03/neil-gaiman-view-from-the-cheap-s=
eats-reading/?mc_cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])
------------------------------------------------------------

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0062262262/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D517=
3218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

The question of why we read and what books actually do for us is as old as=
 the written word itself=2C and as attractive. Galileo saw reading as a wa=
y of having superhuman powers (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/01/14/ga=
lileo-reading/?mc_cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) . For Kafka=2C book=
s were =E2=80=9Cthe axe for the frozen sea within us=E2=80=9D (https://www=
=2Ebrainpickings.org/2014/06/06/kafka-on-books-and-reading/?mc_cid=3D5173218=
563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) ; Carl Sagan held them as =E2=80=9Cproof that huma=
ns are capable of working magic=E2=80=9D (https://www.brainpickings.org/20=
12/05/08/carl-sagan-on-books/?mc_cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) ; Ja=
mes Baldwin found in them a way to change one=E2=80=99s destiny (https://w=
ww.brainpickings.org/2015/04/10/a-rap-on-race-james-baldwin-reading/?mc_ci=
d=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) ; for Polish Nobel laureate Wislawa Szy=
mborska=2C they stood as our ultimate frontier of freedom (https://www.bra=
inpickings.org/2016/02/17/wislawa-szymborska-nonrequired-reading-2/?mc_cid=
=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) .

But one of the finest=2C most dimensional inquiries into the significance=
 of books and the role of reading in human life comes from Neil Gaiman in=
 a beautiful piece titled =E2=80=9CWhy Our Future Depends on Libraries=2C=
 Reading and Daydreaming.=E2=80=9D

Originally delivered as a lecture for The Reading Agency (https://readinga=
gency.org.uk/?mc_cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C an English chari=
ty devoted to giving kids from all backgrounds an equal chance at the good=
 life by fostering an early love of reading=2C the speech was later includ=
ed in The View from the Cheap Seats: Selected Nonfiction (http://www.amazo=
n.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0062262262/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=
=3D[UNIQID]) (public library (http://www.worldcat.org/title/view-from-the=
-cheap-seats-selected-nonfiction/oclc/939277355&referer=3Dbrief_results?mc=
_cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) ) =E2=80=94 the terrific compendium=
 that gave us Gaiman on the power of cautionary questions (https://www.bra=
inpickings.org/2016/05/31/neil-gaiman-the-view-from-the-cheap-seats-bradbu=
ry/?mc_cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) .

Neil Gaiman (Photograph: Amanda Palmer (http://amandapalmer.net?mc_cid=3D5=
173218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) )

Gaiman considers how the act of reading changes us=2C =E2=80=9Cwhat it=E2=
=80=99s good for=E2=80=9D:

Once in New York=2C I listened to a talk about the building of private pri=
sons=E2=80=94a huge growth industry in America. The prison industry needs=
 to plan its future growth =E2=80=94 how many cells are they going to need=
? How many prisoners are there going to be=2C fifteen years from now? And=
 they found they could predict it very easily=2C using a pretty simple alg=
orithm=2C based about asking what percentage of ten- and eleven-year-olds=
 couldn=E2=80=99t read. And certainly couldn=E2=80=99t read for pleasure.

Art by Maurice Sendak for The Big Green Book (https://www.brainpickings.or=
g/2015/06/04/the-big-green-book-robert-graves-maurice-sendak/?mc_cid=3D517=
3218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) by Robert Graves

Echoing Madeleine L=E2=80=99Engle=E2=80=99s spirited 1983 lecture on creat=
ivity=2C censorship=2C and the duty of children=E2=80=99s books (https://w=
ww.brainpickings.org/2014/04/10/dare-to-be-creative-madeleine-l-engle/?mc_=
cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C Gaiman considers how otherwise we=
ll-intentioned adults might thwart the seed of that life-enlarging and som=
etimes even life-saving passion for reading. In a passage of particular ur=
gency for parents and educators=2C he writes:

I don=E2=80=99t think there is such a thing as a bad book for children. Ev=
ery now and again it becomes fashionable among some adults to point at a s=
ubset of children=E2=80=99s books=2C a genre=2C perhaps=2C or an author=2C=
 and to declare them bad books=2C books that children should be stopped fr=
om reading. I=E2=80=99ve seen it happen over and over; Enid Blyton was dec=
lared a bad author=2C so was R. L. Stine=2C so were dozens of others. Comi=
cs have been decried as fostering illiteracy.

It=E2=80=99s tosh. It=E2=80=99s snobbery and it=E2=80=99s foolishness.

There are no bad authors for children=2C that children like and want to re=
ad and seek out=2C because every child is different. They can find the sto=
ries they need to=2C and they bring themselves to stories. A hackneyed=2C=
 worn-out idea isn=E2=80=99t hackneyed and worn out to someone encounterin=
g it for the first time. You don=E2=80=99t discourage children from readin=
g because you feel they are reading the wrong thing. Fiction you do not li=
ke is the gateway drug to other books you may prefer them to read. And not=
 everyone has the same taste as you.

Well-meaning adults can easily destroy a child=E2=80=99s love of reading:=
 stop them reading what they enjoy=2C or give them worthy-but-dull books t=
hat you like=2C the twenty- first-century equivalents of Victorian =E2=80=
=9Cimproving=E2=80=9D literature. You=E2=80=99ll wind up with a generation=
 convinced that reading is uncool and=2C worse=2C unpleasant.

Gaiman then turns to the second key function of literature =E2=80=94 its u=
nparalleled ability to foster empathy. In a sentiment that calls to mind R=
ebecca Solnit=E2=80=99s inspired assertion that =E2=80=9Ca book is a heart=
 that beats in the chest of another=2C=E2=80=9D (https://www.brainpickings=
=2Eorg/2014/10/13/rebecca-solnit-faraway-nearby-reading-writing/?mc_cid=3D51=
73218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) he writes:

When you watch TV or see a film=2C you are looking at things happening to=
 other people. Prose fiction is something you build up from twenty-six let=
ters and a handful of punctuation marks=2C and you=2C and you alone=2C usi=
ng your imagination=2C create a world=2C and people it and look out throug=
h other eyes. You get to feel things=2C visit places and worlds you would=
 never otherwise know. You learn that everyone else out there is a me=2C a=
s well. You=E2=80=99re being someone else=2C and when you return to your o=
wn world=2C you=E2=80=99re going to be slightly changed.

Empathy is a tool for building people into groups=2C for allowing us to fu=
nction as more than self-obsessed individuals.

Art by Maurice Sendak for The Big Green Book (https://www.brainpickings.or=
g/2015/06/04/the-big-green-book-robert-graves-maurice-sendak/?mc_cid=3D517=
3218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) by Robert Graves

In a sentiment reminiscent of Ursula K. Le Guin=E2=80=99s electrifying cas=
e for how imaginative storytelling expands our scope of the possible (http=
s://www.brainpickings.org/2016/05/06/ursula-k-le-guin-freedom-oppression-s=
torytelling/?mc_cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C Gaiman points to=
 a third essential function of fiction in human life =E2=80=94 its ability=
 to introduce us to different versions of the world by envisioning alterna=
te possibilities for the way things are:

Fiction can show you a different world. It can take you somewhere you=E2=
=80=99ve never been. Once you=E2=80=99ve visited other worlds=2C like thos=
e who ate fairy fruit=2C you can never be entirely content with the world=
 that you grew up in. And discontent is a good thing: people can modify an=
d improve their worlds=2C leave them better=2C leave them different=2C if=
 they=E2=80=99re discontented.

But perhaps the surest way to foil a budding love of reading is to cut off=
 access to books altogether=2C and there is no greater hedge against that=
 hazard than the library =E2=80=94 that sacred place Thoreau once extolled=
 as a glorious =E2=80=9Cwilderness of books.=E2=80=9D (https://www.brainpi=
ckings.org/2015/04/23/thoreau-on-libraries/?mc_cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[=
UNIQID]) (=E2=80=9CWhen a library is open=2C no matter its size or shape=
=2C=E2=80=9D Bill Moyers wrote in his foreword to a recent photographic lo=
ve letter to libraries (https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/04/09/the-publi=
c-library-robert-dawson-book/?mc_cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C=
 =E2=80=9Cdemocracy is open=2C too.=E2=80=9D) Gaiman recounts the formativ=
e role of the library in his own life:

I was lucky. I had an excellent local library growing up. I had the kind o=
f parents who could be persuaded to drop me off in the library on their wa=
y to work in my summer holidays=2C and the kind of librarians who did not=
 mind a small=2C unaccompanied boy heading back into the children=E2=80=99=
s library every morning and working his way through the card catalogue=2C=
 looking for books with ghosts or magic or rockets in them=2C looking for=
 vampires or detectives or witches or wonders. And when I had finished rea=
ding the children=E2=80=99s library I began on the adult books.

Gaiman was fortunate that the librarians tasked with nurturing his love of=
 reading were the kind who inspire poems (https://www.brainpickings.org/20=
15/08/07/if-librarians-were-honest-the-artists-library/?mc_cid=3D517321856=
3&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) and not the kind who tried to bar pioneering astrona=
ut Ronald McNair from his childhood library (https://www.brainpickings.org=
/2016/06/06/ronald-mcnair-storycorps-callings/?mc_cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=
=3D[UNIQID]) . With an affectionate eye to the librarians of his youth=2C=
 Gaiman reflects:

They were good librarians. They liked books and they liked the books being=
 read. They taught me how to order books from other libraries on interlibr=
ary loans. They had no snobbery about anything I read. They just seemed to=
 like that there was this wide-eyed little boy who loved to read=2C and th=
ey would talk to me about the books I was reading=2C they would find me ot=
her books in a series=2C they would help. They treated me as another reade=
r =E2=80=94 nothing less=2C nothing more =E2=80=94 which meant they treate=
d me with respect. I was not used to being treated with respect as an eigh=
t-year-old.

Libraries are about Freedom. Freedom to read=2C freedom of ideas=2C freedo=
m of communication. They are about education (which is not a process that=
 finishes the day we leave school or university)=2C about entertainment=2C=
 about making safe spaces=2C and about access to information.

Illustration from The Book of Memory Gaps (https://www.brainpickings.org/2=
015/07/22/the-book-of-memory-gaps-cecilia-ruiz/?mc_cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=
=3D[UNIQID]) by Cecilia Ruiz

Writing nearly a century after Hermann Hesse=E2=80=99s magnificent manifes=
to for why the book will never lose its magic (https://www.brainpickings.o=
rg/2016/06/07/the-magic-of-the-book-hermann-hesse-my-belief/?mc_cid=3D5173=
218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) no matter how technology evolves=2C Gaiman borr=
ows a prefect metaphor to substantiate his belief that books will endure i=
n and perhaps past the age of screens:

As Douglas Adams once pointed out to me=2C over twenty years before the Ki=
ndle showed up=2C a physical book is like a shark. Sharks are old: there w=
ere sharks in the ocean before the dinosaurs. And the reason there are sti=
ll sharks around is that sharks are better at being sharks than anything e=
lse is. Physical books are tough=2C hard to destroy=2C bath resistant=2C s=
olar operated=2C feel good in your hand: they are good at being books=2C a=
nd there will always be a place for them.

But Gaiman takes care not to confuse the medium with the message =E2=80=94=
 it is reading that counts=2C and its rewards are medium-agnostic. He writ=
es:

We need libraries. We need books. We need literate citizens.

I do not care =E2=80=94 I do not believe it matters =E2=80=94 whether thes=
e books are paper or digital=2C whether you are reading on a scroll or scr=
olling on a screen. The content is the important thing.

But a book is also the content=2C and that=E2=80=99s important.

Books are the way that we communicate with the dead. The way that we learn=
 lessons from those who are no longer with us=2C that humanity has built o=
n itself=2C progressed=2C made knowledge incremental rather than something=
 that has to be relearned=2C over and over. There are tales that are older=
 than most countries=2C tales that have long outlasted the cultures and th=
e buildings in which they were first told.

These tales have survived on the shoulders of people who have done their p=
art to transmit them forward =E2=80=94 something Gaiman examined in his ex=
cellent lecture on how stories last (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/06=
/16/neil-gaiman-how-stories-last/?mc_cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])=
 . He considers what it would take to uphold our own responsibilities to t=
he future =E2=80=94 as readers=2C as writers=2C as citizens=2C and as memb=
ers of the storytelling species:

I believe we have an obligation to read for pleasure=2C in private and in=
 public places. If we read for pleasure=2C if others see us reading=2C the=
n we learn=2C we exercise our imaginations. We show others that reading is=
 a good thing.

We have an obligation to support libraries. To use libraries=2C to encoura=
ge others to use libraries=2C to protest the closure of libraries. If you=
 do not value libraries then you do not value information or culture or wi=
sdom. You are silencing the voices of the past and you are damaging the fu=
ture.

We have an obligation to read aloud to our children. To read them things t=
hey enjoy. To read to them stories we are already tired of. To do the voic=
es=2C to make it interesting=2C and not to stop reading to them just becau=
se they learn to read to themselves. We have an obligation to use reading-=
aloud time as bonding time=2C as time when no phones are being checked=2C=
 when the distractions of the world are put aside.

We have an obligation to use the language. To push ourselves: to find out=
 what words mean and how to deploy them=2C to communicate clearly=2C to sa=
y what we mean. We must not attempt to freeze language=2C or to pretend it=
 is a dead thing that must be revered=2C but we should use it as a living=
 thing=2C that flows=2C that borrows words=2C that allows meanings and pro=
nunciations to change with time.

We writers =E2=80=94 and especially writers for children=2C but all writer=
s =E2=80=94 have an obligation to our readers: it=E2=80=99s the obligation=
 to write true things=2C especially important when we are creating tales o=
f people who do not exist in places that never were =E2=80=94 to understan=
d that truth is not in what happens but in what it tells us about who we a=
re. Fiction is the lie that tells the truth=2C after all. We have an oblig=
ation not to bore our readers=2C but to make them need to turn the pages.=
 One of the best cures for a reluctant reader=2C after all=2C is a tale th=
ey cannot stop themselves from reading. And while we must tell our readers=
 true things and give them weapons and give them armor and pass on whateve=
r wisdom we have gleaned from our short stay on this green world=2C we hav=
e an obligation not to preach=2C not to lecture=2C not to force predigeste=
d morals and messages down our readers=E2=80=99 throats like adult birds f=
eeding their babies pre-masticated maggots; and we have an obligation neve=
r=2C ever=2C
under any circumstances=2C to write anything for children to read that we=
 would not want to read ourselves.

We have an obligation to understand and to acknowledge that as writers for=
 children we are doing important work=2C because if we mess it up and writ=
e dull books that turn children away from reading and from books=2C we=E2=
=80=99ve lessened our own future and diminished theirs.

Writing more than two centuries after William Blake=E2=80=99s searing defe=
nse of the imagination (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/07/14/william-b=
lake-john-trusler-letter/?mc_cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C Gaim=
an points to the same supreme human faculty as our greatest obligation:

We all =E2=80=94 adults and children=2C writers and readers =E2=80=94 have=
 an obligation to daydream. We have an obligation to imagine. It is easy t=
o pretend that nobody can change anything=2C that we are in a world in whi=
ch society is huge and the individual is less than nothing: an atom in a w=
all=2C a grain of rice in a rice field. But the truth is=2C individuals ch=
ange their world over and over=2C individuals make the future=2C and they=
 do it by imagining that things can be different.

[=E2=80=A6]

Just look around this room=E2=80=A6 Everything you can see=2C including th=
e walls=2C was=2C at some point=2C imagined. Someone decided it might be e=
asier to sit on a chair than on the ground and imagined the chair. Someone=
 had to imagine a way that I could talk to you in London right now without=
 us all getting rained on. This room and the things in it=2C and all the o=
ther things in this building=2C in this city=2C exist because=2C over and=
 over and over=2C people imagined things. They daydreamed=2C they pondered=
=2C they made things that didn=E2=80=99t quite work=2C they described thin=
gs that didn=E2=80=99t yet exist to people who laughed at them.

And then=2C in time=2C they succeeded. Political movements=2C personal mov=
ements=2C all begin with people imagining another way of existing.

Gaiman=E2=80=99s final obligation is of especially resonant relevance toda=
y:

We have an obligation to tell our politicians what we want=2C to vote agai=
nst politicians of whatever party who do not understand the value of readi=
ng in creating worthwhile citizens=2C who do not want to act to preserve a=
nd protect knowledge and encourage literacy. This is not a matter of party=
 politics. This is a matter of common humanity.

Complement this particular portion of the wholly magnificent The View from=
 the Cheap Seats (http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0062262262/braipi=
ck-20?mc_cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) with Hermann Hesse on the th=
ree types of readers (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/07/11/hermann-hes=
se-types-of-readers/?mc_cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C Ursula K.=
