** Bruce Lee=E2=80=99s Never-Before-Seen Writings on Willpower=2C Emotion=
=2C Reason=2C Memory=2C Imagination=2C and Confidence (https://www.brainpi=
ckings.org/2016/08/01/bruce-lee-notebook/?mc_cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[U=
NIQID])
------------------------------------------------------------

http://apple.co/2a9LWkL?mc_cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

Although Bruce Lee (November 27=2C 1940=E2=80=93July 20=2C 1973) is best k=
nown for his legendary legacy in martial arts and film=2C he was also one=
 of the most underappreciated philosophers of the twentieth century=2C ins=
trumental in introducing Eastern traditions to Western audiences. A philos=
ophy major in collge=2C he fused ancient ideas with his own singular ethos=
 informed by the intersection of physical and psychological discipline=2C=
 the most famous manifestation of which is his water metaphor for resilien=
ce (https://www.brainpickings.org/2013/05/29/like-water-bruce-lee-artist-o=
f-life/?mc_cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) .

Early in his career=2C Lee was systematically sidelined by Hollywood=E2=80=
=99s studio system=2C which operated with extreme racial bias and still us=
ed white actors in yellowface to portray Asian characters based on flat st=
ereotypes. Over and over=2C Lee was told in no uncertain terms that white=
 audiences simply wouldn=E2=80=99t accept an Asian man as a lead character=
 in a movie.

Bruce Lee (Photograph courtesy of the Bruce Lee Foundation archive)

Even when he finally broke through and was cast as a lead=2C the studios c=
ontinued to treat him as a brainless robot=2C there to entertain with his=
 kung-fu skills. When they tried to cut all the philosophy out of Enter th=
e Dragon because they wanted a vacantly entertaining action movie=2C Lee r=
efused to go on set for two weeks=2C insisting that the kung-fu and the ph=
ilosophy were inextricably entwined=2C each the vehicle for the other. Hol=
lywood eventually had to relent and it was precisely the philosophical dim=
ension that rendered the movie =E2=80=94 just before the release of which=
 Lee met his untimely death =E2=80=94 a cultural icon and a beacon of raci=
al empowerment associated with the Black Power movement=2C later acquired=
 by the Library of Congress as a =E2=80=9Cculturally=2C historically=2C or=
 aesthetically significant=E2=80=9D artifact.

Lee saw philosophy as inseparable from everyday life=2C just as he saw the=
 mind as inseparable from the body=2C each end of the battery constantly c=
harging the other. He recorded his rigorous workout routine alongside his=
 philosophical meditations=2C which he fleshed out in the course of living=
=2E Like Oliver Sacks=2C who carried a notebook everywhere (https://www.brai=
npickings.org/2015/06/19/oliver-sacks-thom-gunn-writing/?mc_cid=3D51732185=
63&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C Lee always had a tiny 2=C3=973=E2=80=B3 pocketb=
ook with him=2C which he filled with everything from training regimens to=
 the phone numbers of his pupils (who included trainees like Chuck Norris=
 and Steve McQueen) to poems=2C affirmations=2C and philosophical reflecti=
ons. Even his handwriting=2C meticulously neat and measured to fit the tin=
y page=2C radiates Lee=E2=80=99s formidable discipline and orderliness.

Bruce Lee (Photograph courtesy of the Bruce Lee Foundation archive)

But perhaps the most notable portion of his pocketbooks =E2=80=94 or day t=
imers=2C as they were called =E2=80=94 were his affirmations=2C reminiscen=
t of the rules of conduct (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/01/13/andre-=
gide-journals-rules-of-conduct/?mc_cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) No=
bel laureate Andr=C3=A9 Gide penned in his youthful journal and of artist=
 Eug=C3=A8ne Delacroix=E2=80=99s diaristic self-counsel (https://www.brain=
pickings.org/2015/04/17/delacroix-journal-solitude/?mc_cid=3D5173218563&mc=
_eid=3D[UNIQID]) . In these notes to himself=2C Lee articulated his perso=
nal philosophies aimed concretely at his own growth but resonating with un=
iversally applicable insight into our common psychology=2C behavior=2C and=
 human nature.

With special permission from the Bruce Lee estate (http://brucelee.com?mc_=
cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C here is an exclusive look at seve=
ral pages from his 1968 pocketbook=2C penned shortly before Lee=E2=80=99s=
 twenty-eighth birthday=2C each transcribed below:

Archival material with exclusive permission from the Bruce Lee Foundation=
 archive

WILL POWER: =E2=80=94

Recognizing that the power of will is the supreme court over all over depa=
rtments of my mind=2C I will exercise it daily=2C when I need the urge to=
 action for any purpose; and I will form HABIT designed to bring the power=
 of my will into action at least once daily.

EMOTION: =E2=80=94

Realizing that my emotions are both POSITIVE and negative I will form dail=
y HABITS which will encourage the development of the POSITIVE EMOTIONS=2C=
 and aid me in converting the negative emotions into some form of useful a=
ction.

REASON: =E2=80=94

Recognizing that both my positive & negative emotions may be dangerous if=
 they are not controlled and guided to desirable ends=2C I will submit all=
 my desires=2C aims and purposes to my faculties of reason=2C and I will b=
e guided by it in giving expression to these.

IMAGINATION: =E2=80=94

Recognizing the need for sound PLANS and IDEAS for the attainment of my de=
sires=2C I will develop my imagination by calling upon it daily for help i=
n the formation of my plans.

MEMORY: =E2=80=94

Recognizing the value of an alert memory=2C I will encourage mine to becom=
e alert by taking care to impress it clearly with all thoughts I wish to r=
ecall=2C and by associating those thoughts with related subjects which I m=
ay call to mind frequently.

SUBCONSCIOUS MIND: =E2=80=94

Recognizing the influence of my subconscious mind over my power of will=2C=
 I shall take care to submit to it a clear and definite picture of my CLEA=
R PURPOSE in life and all minor purposes leading to my major purpose=2C an=
d I shall keep this picture CONSTANTLY BEFORE my subconscious mind by REPE=
ATING IT DAILY.

CONSCIENCE: =E2=80=94

Recognizing that my emotions often err in their over-enthusiasm=2C and my=
 faculty of reason often is without the warmth of feeling that is necessar=
y to enable me to combine justice with mercy in my judgments=2C I will enc=
ourage my conscience to guide me as to what is right & what is wrong=2C bu=
t I will never set aside the verdicts it renders=2C no matter what may be=
 the cost of carrying them out.

When Lee felt that he had arrived at a particularly significant idea=2C he=
 wrote it on the unlined back of a plain 3=C3=975=E2=80=B3 lined yellow no=
tecard=2C which he signed=2C almost like a will or perhaps a contract with=
 himself. He would often refine or copy reflections first recorded in his=
 pocketbook onto the notecards reserved for only his firmest convictions a=
nd deepest dedications.

What makes the affirmations especially notable is that they fuse ancient p=
hilosophical and spiritual traditions (particularly Zen Buddhism=E2=80=99s=
 ideas about character=2C the self=2C and the ego (https://www.brainpickin=
gs.org/2015/01/30/d-t-suzuki-essays-in-zen-buddhism/?mc_cid=3D5173218563&m=
c_eid=3D[UNIQID]) )=2C questionable New Agey magical thinking=2C and habi=
ts of mind which contemporary psychology has since proven fruitful =E2=80=
=94 a reminder that our personhood is a mashup of our era and our culture=
=2C with all their inherent knowledges and ignorances=2C and it is the way=
 we combine the elements at our disposal that makes us who we are.

Archival material with exclusive permission from the Bruce Lee Foundation=
 archive

You will never get any more out of life than you expect

Keep your mind on the things you want and off those you don=E2=80=99t

Things live by moving and gain strength as they go

Be a calm beholder of what is happening around you

There is a difference a) the world b) our reaction to it

Be aware of our conditioning! Drop and dissolve inner blockage

Inner to outer ~~~ we start by dissolving our attitude not by altering out=
er condition

See that there is no one to fight=2C only an illusion to see through

No one can hurt you unless you allow him to

Inwardly=2C psychologically=2C be a nobody

Archival material with exclusive permission from the Bruce Lee Foundation=
 archive

I know that I have the ability to ACHIEVE the object of my DEFINITE PURPOS=
E in life; therefore I DEMAND of myself persistent=2C continuous action to=
ward its attainment=2C and I here and now promise to render such action.

I realize the DOMINATING THOUGHTS of my mind will eventually reproduce the=
mselves in outward=2C physical action=2C and gradually transform themselve=
s into physical reality; therefore I will CONCENTRATE my thoughts for 30 m=
in. daily upon the task of thinking of the person I intend to become=2C th=
ereby creating in my mind a clear MENTAL PICTURE.

I know through the principle of autosuggestion=2C any desire that I PERSIS=
TENTLY hold will eventually seek expression through some practical means o=
f attaining the object back of it; therefore=2C I will devote 10 min. dail=
y to DEMANDING of myself the development of SELF-CONFIDENCE.

I have clearly written down a description of my DEFINITE CHIEF AIM in life=
=2C and I will never stop trying until I shall have developed sufficient s=
elf-confidence for its attainment.

Complement with Lee on the crucial difference between pride and self-estee=
m (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/12/18/bruce-lee-artist-of-life-self-=
esteem/?mc_cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C then tune into the exc=
ellent new Bruce Lee podcast (http://apple.co/2a9LWkL?mc_cid=3D5173218563&=
mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C in which Lee=E2=80=99s daughter=2C Shannon=2C and=
