** Diane Ackerman on the Evolutionary and Existential Purpose of Deep Play=
 (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/08/04/diane-ackerman-deep-play/?mc_ci=
d=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])
------------------------------------------------------------

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0679771352/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D517=
3218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

One July morning during a research trip to the small New England island of=
 Nantucket=2C home to pioneering astronomer Maria Mitchell (https://www.br=
ainpickings.org/2016/08/01/maria-mitchell-diary-spider/?mc_cid=3D517321856=
3&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C I had a most unusual experience. Midway through=
 my daily swim in the ocean=2C my peripheral vision was drawn to what at f=
irst appeared to be a snorkel. But as I looked directly at the curious pro=
trusion=2C I realized it was the long glistening neck of a stately bird=2C=
 gliding over the nearly waveless surface a few away. By some irresistible=
 instinct=2C I began swimming gently toward the bird=2C assuming it would=
 fly away whenever my proximity became too uncomfortable.

But it didn=E2=80=99t. Instead=2C it allowed my approach =E2=80=94 for it=
 was deliberate permission that this majestic bird gave me=2C first assess=
ing me with a calm but cautious eye=2C then choosing not to lift off or ev=
en change course as this large ungraceful mammal drew near. I came so clos=
e that I could see my own reflection in the bird=E2=80=99s eye=2C now rega=
rding me with what I took to be =E2=80=94 or=2C perhaps=2C projected to be=
 =E2=80=94 a silent benevolence.

We began swimming side by side=2C no more than a wingspan away from one an=
other=2C and I found myself awash in awe amid the gentle waves=2C entrance=
d in what could best be described as a transcendent experience =E2=80=94 t=
he kind that calls to mind=2C and called to mind in that very moment in th=
e water=2C Alan Lightman=E2=80=99s moving encounter with the ospreys (http=
s://www.brainpickings.org/2014/01/15/alan-lightman-accidental-universe-sci=
ence-spirituality/?mc_cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) . In this small=
 act ablaze with absolute presence=2C I felt I had been granted access to=
 something enormous and eternal.

The experience was so intensely invigorating in part because it was wholly=
 new to me=2C but it is far from uncommon. It belongs to the spectrum of e=
xperience which Diane Ackerman=2C one of the greatest science storytellers=
 of our time=2C describes in Deep Play (http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/=
ASIN/0679771352/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) (publi=
c library (http://www.worldcat.org/title/deep-play/oclc/39533033&referer=
=3Dbrief_results?mc_cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) ) =E2=80=94 a bew=
itchingly inquiry into those moods colored by =E2=80=9Ca combination of cl=
arity=2C wild enthusiasm=2C saturation in the moment=2C and wonder=2C=E2=
=80=9D which render us in a state of =E2=80=9Cwaking trance.=E2=80=9D

Ackerman =E2=80=94 who has previously written beautifully about the secret=
 life of the senses (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/08/06/diane-ackerm=
an-a-natural-history-of-the-senses-2/?mc_cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQI=
D]) =2C our poetic communion with the cosmos (https://www.brainpickings.or=
g/2013/02/19/diane-ackerman-the-planets-a-cosmic-pastoral/?mc_cid=3D517321=
8563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C and the darkest depths of the human experienc=
e (https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/11/14/diane-ackerman-a-slender-threa=
d/?mc_cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =E2=80=94 reclaims and subverts=
 the phrase =E2=80=9Cdeep play=E2=80=9D from Jeremy Bentham=2C founding fa=
ther of utilitarianism=2C who used it pejoratively in the 18th century to=
 connote any high-stakes activity engaging in which he deemed irrational b=
ecause =E2=80=9Cthe marginal utility of what you stand to win is grossly o=
utweighed by the disutility of what you stand to lose.=E2=80=9D But Ackerm=
an argues that the risk involved in activities of that sort only amplifies=
 their romance.

She considers what deep play is and why it appeals to us so profoundly:

We long for its heights=2C which some people often visit and others must l=
earn to find=2C but everyone experiences as replenishing. Opportunities fo=
r deep play abound. In its thrall we become ideal versions of ourselves=E2=
=80=A6 [Its] many moods and varieties help to define who we are and all w=
e wish to be.

Art by Sydney Smith from The White Cat and the Monk (https://www.brainpick=
ings.org/2016/04/11/the-white-cat-and-the-monk/?mc_cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=
=3D[UNIQID]) =2C a 9th-century ode to the diversity of transcendent exper=
iences

Before diving into the psychological and spiritual dimensions of deep play=
=2C Ackerman examines play itself and its evolutionary function as an inde=
lible part of sentience and a measure of the evolution of consciousness pe=
rhaps more accurate than what we refer to as intelligence. She writes:

Why play at all? Every element of the human saga requires play. We evolved=
 through play. Our culture thrives on play. Courtship includes high theate=
r=2C rituals=2C and ceremonies of play. Ideas are playful reverberations o=
f the mind. Language is a playing with words until they can impersonate ph=
ysical objects and abstract ideas.

[=E2=80=A6]

It=E2=80=99s so familiar to us=2C so deeply ingrained in the matrix of our=
 childhood=2C that we take it for granted. But consider this: ants don=E2=
=80=99t play. They don=E2=80=99t need to. Programmed for certain behaviors=
=2C they automatically perform them from birth. Learning through repetitio=
n=2C honed skills=2C and ingenuity isn=E2=80=99t required in their heritag=
e. The more an animal needs to learn in order to survive=2C the more it ne=
eds to play=E2=80=A6 What we call intelligence =E2=80=A6 may not be life=
=E2=80=99s pinnacle at all=2C but simply one mode of knowing=2C one we hap=
pen to master and cherish. Play is widespread among animals because it inv=
ites problem-solving=2C allowing a creature to test its limits and develop=
 strategies. In a dangerous world=2C where dramas change daily=2C survival=
 belongs to the agile not the idle. We may think of play as optional=2C a=
 casual activity. But play is fundamental to evolution. Without play=2C hu=
mans and many other animals would perish.

Art by Christian Robinson from Leo: A Ghost Story (https://www.brainpickin=
gs.org/2015/12/14/leo-a-ghost-mac-barnett/?mc_cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[=
UNIQID])

It is hardly happenstance that the word =E2=80=9Cplay=E2=80=9D was central=
 to how Einstein thought of the secret to his genius =E2=80=94 he used the=
 term =E2=80=9Ccombinatory play=E2=80=9D (https://www.brainpickings.org/20=
13/08/14/how-einstein-thought-combinatorial-creativity/?mc_cid=3D517321856=
3&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) to describe how his mind works. Ackerman considers w=
hat it is that makes play so psychologically fruitful and alluring to us=
=2C plunging into its ancient cultural history:

The world of play favors exuberance=2C license=2C abandon. [In it=2C] sel=
ves can be revised.

[=E2=80=A6]

Above all=2C play requires freedom. One chooses to play. Play=E2=80=99s ru=
les may be enforced=2C but play is not like life=E2=80=99s other dramas. I=
t happens outside ordinary life=2C and it requires freedom.

Art by Katrin Stangl from Strong as a Bear (https://www.brainpickings.org/=
2016/06/14/strong-as-a-bear-katrin-stangl/?mc_cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[=
UNIQID])

Ackerman maps the etymological ecosystem of play:

Most forms of play involve competition=2C against oneself or others=2C and=
 test one=E2=80=99s skills=2C cunning=2C or courage. One might even argue=
 that all play is a contest of one sort or another. The adversary may be a=
 mountain=2C a chess-playing computer=2C or an incarnation of evil. To pla=
y is to risk: to risk is to play. The word fight derives from the word pla=
y. Medieval tournaments were ritualized battles that followed strict rules=
=2E So are wrestling=2C boxing=2C and fencing matches. Ceremonial violence=
 =E2=80=94 at a sacred place=2C in which special clothes are worn=2C time=
 limits must be obeyed=2C rules are followed=2C rituals are performed=2C t=
he action is alarmingly tense=2C and the outcome is unknown =E2=80=94 is e=
lemental to play. Festive dancing may seem peaceful by comparison=2C and i=
ndeed in Anglo-Saxon=2C play was plega=2C which meant singing or dancing g=
estures=2C clapping=2C quick movements.

But when we peer even farther back into its origins=2C we discover that pl=
ay=E2=80=99s original meaning was quite different=2C something altogether=
 more urgent and abstract. In Indo-European=2C plegan meant to risk=2C cha=
nce=2C expose oneself to hazard. A pledge was integral to the act of play=
=2C as was danger (cognate words are peril and plight). Play=E2=80=99s ori=
ginal purpose was to make a pledge to someone or something by risking one=
=E2=80=99s life. Who or what might that someone or something be? Possibili=
ties abound=2C including a relative=2C a tribal leader=2C a god=2C or a mo=
ral trait such as honor or courage. At its heart=2C plegan reverberated wi=
th ethical or religious values. It also contained the idea of being tightl=
y fastened or engaged. Soon plegan became associated with performing a sac=
red act or administering justice=2C and it often appeared in ceremonies.

But while simple play may have its timeless appeal=2C Ackerman focuses on=
 a deeper and more transcendent kind of play =E2=80=94 something more rapt=
urous and closer to ecstasy=2C something that helps us contact our hidden=
 wholeness (https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/11/03/parker-palmer-hidden-=
wholeness/?mc_cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) and is perhaps even req=
uired for us to feel whole. She explores the essential point of difference=
:

Deep play is the ecstatic form of play. In its thrall=2C all the play elem=
ents are visible=2C but they=E2=80=99re taken to intense and transcendent=
 heights. Thus=2C deep play should really be classified by mood=2C not act=
ivity. It testifies to how something happens=2C not what happens. Games do=
n=E2=80=99t guarantee deep play=2C but some activities are prone to it: ar=
t=2C religion=2C risk-taking=2C and some sports =E2=80=94 especially those=
 that take place in relatively remote=2C silent=2C and floaty environments=
=2C such as scuba diving=2C parachuting=2C hang gliding=2C mountain climbi=
ng.

Deep play always involves the sacred and holy=2C sometimes hidden in the m=
ost unlikely or humble places =E2=80=94 amid towering shelves of rock in N=
epal; crouched over print in a dimly lit room; slipping on AstroTurf; wear=
ing a coconut-shell mask. We spend our lives in pursuit of moments that wi=
ll allow these altered states to happen.

Art by Maurice Sendak from Kenny=E2=80=99s Window (https://www.brainpickin=
gs.org/2016/01/08/kennys-window-maurice-sendak/?mc_cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=
=3D[UNIQID]) =2C his forgotten=2C philosophical first children=E2=80=99s=
 book

Ackerman narrows in on the seemingly subtle yet monumental difference betw=
een the two states most closely associated with deep play=2C rapture and e=
cstasy:

Rapture and ecstasy are not themselves deep play=2C but they=E2=80=99re ce=
ntral components of it.

Rapture means=2C literally=2C being =E2=80=9Cseized by force=2C=E2=80=9D a=
s if one were a prey animal who is carried away. Caught in the talons of a=
 transcendent rapture=2C one is gripped=2C elevated=2C and trapped at a fe=
arsome height. To the ancient Greeks=2C this feeling often foretold malevo=
lence and danger =E2=80=94 other words that drink from the same rapturous=
 source are rapacious=2C rabid=2C ravenous=2C ravage=2C rape=2C usurp=2C s=
urreptitious. Birds of prey that plunge from the skies to gore their victi=
ms are known as raptors. Seized by a jagged and violent force=2C the enrap=
tured are carried aloft to their ultimate doom.

Ecstasy also means to be gripped by passion=2C but from a slightly differe=
nt perspective: rapture is vertical=2C ecstasy horizontal. Rapture is high=
-flying=2C ecstasy occurs on the ground. For some reason=2C the ancient Gr=
eeks were obsessed with the symbol of standing=2C and relied on that one i=
mage for countless ideas=2C feelings=2C and objects. As a result=2C a grea=
t many of our words today simply reflect where or how things stand: stanch=
ion=2C status=2C stare=2C staunch=2C steadfast=2C statute=2C and constant.=
 But there are also hundreds of unexpected ones=2C such as stank (standing=
 water)=2C stallion (standing in a stall)=2C star (standing in the sky)=2C=
 restaurant (standing place for the wanderer)=2C prostate (standing in fro=
nt of the bladder)=2C and so on. To the Greeks=2C ecstasy meant to stand o=
utside oneself. How is that possible? Through existential engineering. =E2=
=80=9CGive me a place to stand=2C=E2=80=9D Archimedes proclaimed in the th=
ird century B.C.=2C =E2=80=9Cand I will move the earth.=E2=80=9D Levered b=
y ecstasy=2C one springs out of
one=E2=80=99s mind. Thrown free of one=E2=80=99s normal self=2C a person s=
tands in another place=2C on the limits of body=2C society=2C and reason=
=2C watching the known world dwindle in the distance (a spot standing far=
 away). The euphoria of flying in dreams=2C or the longing to fly through=
 the ocean with dolphins=2C fills us with rapture.

It is hardly any surprise that elements of deep play can be found in most=
 of our major efforts to make sense of the human experience=2C from Ancien=
t Greek philosophy to Freud=E2=80=99s notion of =E2=80=9Coceanic feeling=
=E2=80=9D to Mihalyi Csikszentmihalyi=E2=80=99s concept of =E2=80=9Cflow.=
=E2=80=9D (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/01/28/mark-strand-creativity=
/?mc_cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) Turning once again to the lens o=
f language =E2=80=94 for=2C lest we forget=2C language is our mightiest ve=
hicle for the self (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/05/24/elizabeth-ale=
xander-power-and-possibility-writing/?mc_cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQI=
D]) =E2=80=94 Ackerman contemplates deep play=E2=80=99s singular quality o=
f being:

Deep play is a fascinating hallmark of being human; it reveals our need to=
 seek a special brand of transcendence=2C with a passion that makes thrill=
-seeking explicable=2C creativity possible=2C and religion inevitable. Per=
haps religion seems an unlikely example of playing=2C but if you look at r=
eligious rites and festivals=2C you=E2=80=99ll see all the play elements=
=2C and also how deep that play can become. Religious rituals usually incl=
ude dance=2C worship=2C music=2C and decoration. They swallow time. They a=
re ecstatic=2C absorbing=2C rejuvenating. The word =E2=80=9Cprayer=E2=80=
=9D derives from the Latin precarius=2C and contains the idea of uncertain=
ty and risk. Will the entreaty be answered? Life or death may depend on th=
e outcome.

Reading over a journal entry from her own youth=2C in which her long-ago s=
elf describes the transcendence of travel in a way that calls to mind Albe=
rt Camus=E2=80=99s longer-ago meditation on why we voyage (https://www.bra=
inpickings.org/2015/11/30/albert-camus-travel-lyrical-critical-essays/?mc_=
cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C Ackerman extrapolates a common ro=
ot of deep play across its many guises:

One enters into an alternate reality with its own rules=2C values=2C and e=
xpectations. One sheds much of one=E2=80=99s culture=2C with its countless=
 technical and moral demands=2C as one draws on a wholly new and sense-rav=
ishing way of life=E2=80=A6 One chooses to divest oneself of preconception=
s=2C hand-me-down ideas=2C and shopworn opinions=2C chooses to wipe the me=
ntal slate clean=2C chooses to be naive and wholly open to the world=2C as=
 one once was as a child. If cynicism is inevitable as one ages=2C so is t=
he yearning for innocence. To children heaven is being an adult=2C and to=
 adults heaven is being children again.

[=E2=80=A6]

As the world reduces to a small brilliant space=2C where every thought and=
 move is vital to one=E2=80=99s salvation=2C one=E2=80=99s scattered energ=
y suddenly has a center. Only then do all of our senses spring alert=2C an=
d every sensation matters. At the same time=2C the rest of the world reced=
es. One is temporarily unshackled from life=E2=80=99s chains =E2=80=94 the=
 family ones=2C the work ones=2C the ones we wear as self-imposed weights.

Illustration by Lisbeth Zwerger for a special edition of Alice in Wonderla=
nd (https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/07/07/best-illustrations-alice-in-w=
onderland/?mc_cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])

But perhaps the single most perceptible characteristic of deep play is the=
 way in which it alters our already warped experience of time (https://www=
=2Ebrainpickings.org/2013/07/15/time-warped-claudia-hammond/?mc_cid=3D517321=
8563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) by summoning us to that place where impulsivity a=
nd control intersect to grant us absolute access to presence (https://www.=
brainpickings.org/2016/04/27/time-felt-marc-wittmann/?mc_cid=3D5173218563&=
mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) . In a passage that calls to mind Kafka=E2=80=99s asse=
rtion that =E2=80=9Creality is never and nowhere more accessible than in t=
he immediate moment of one=E2=80=99s own life=2C=E2=80=9D () Ackerman cons=
iders the reality-concentrating power of deep play through the prism of ti=
me:

In deep play=2C one=E2=80=99s sense of time no longer originates within on=
eself.

[=E2=80=A6]

We want to muscle into life and feel its real power and sweep. We want to=
 drink from the source. In rare moments of deep play=2C we can lay aside o=
ur sense of self=2C shed time=E2=80=99s continuum=2C ignore pain=2C and si=
t quietly in the absolute present=2C watching the world=E2=80=99s ordinary=
 miracles=E2=80=A6 When it happens we experience a sense of revelation and=
 gratitude. Nothing need be thought or said. There is a way of beholding t=
hat is a form of prayer.

[=E2=80=A6]

When one enters the realm of deep play=2C the sacred playground where only=
 the present moment matters=2C one=E2=80=99s history and future vanish. On=
e doesn=E2=80=99t remember one=E2=80=99s past=2C needs=2C expectations=2C=
 worries=2C real or imaginary sins. The deep-play world is fresh=2C wholly=
 absorbing=2C and full of its own unique wisdom and demands. Being able to=
 temporarily step outside of normal life=E2=80=94while keeping one=E2=80=
=99s senses alert =E2=80=94 is indeed like being reborn. To erase all memo=
ries and yearnings =E2=80=94 to be vigorously alive without self-awareness=
 =E2=80=94 can provide a brief return to innocence.

In the remainder of the wholly enchanting Deep Play (http://www.amazon.com=
/exec/obidos/ASIN/0679771352/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[UN=
IQID]) =2C Ackerman goes on to explore the types of experiences that grant=
 us entry into this sacred world and the moods=2C mental states=2C and ori=
entations of spirit that make us better able to conjure up the temperament=
 of receptivity needed to experience deep play. Complement with Ackerman o=
n the science of smell (https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/04/10/how-smell=
-works-diane-ackerman-senses/?mc_cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C=
 what Earth=E2=80=99s nocturnal portrait from space reveals about who we a=
re (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/06/18/diane-ackerman-the-human-age-=
2/?mc_cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C and her beautiful poems for=
 the planets (https://www.brainpickings.org/2013/02/19/diane-ackerman-the-=
planets-a-cosmic-pastoral/?mc_cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) .


