** Virginia Woolf on Clothing as a Vehicle of Identity=2C the Fluidity of=
 Gender=2C and the Trans Dimension of Human Nature (https://www.brainpicki=
ngs.org/2016/08/01/virginia-woolf-orlando-clothing-gender/?mc_cid=3D517321=
8563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])
------------------------------------------------------------

http://www.amazon.com/Orlando-Biography-Virginia-Woolf/dp/015670160X/?tag=
=3Dbraipick-20Almost&mc_cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID] a century befo=
re Emily Spivack came to explore how clothes =E2=80=9Chelp us assert our i=
dentity or aspirations=E2=80=9D in her wonderful inquiry into the emotiona=
l dimension of clothing (https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/08/26/worn-sto=
ries-emily-spivack/?mc_cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C which insp=
ired a recent episode (http://www.npr.org/programs/invisibilia/485605882/t=
he-secret-emotional-life-of-clothes?showDate=3D2016-07-22&mc_cid=3D5173218=
563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) of NPR=E2=80=99s excellent Invisibilia=2C Virginia=
 Woolf wove the subject into Orlando: A Biography (http://www.amazon.com/O=
rlando-A-Biography-Virginia-Woolf/dp/015670160X/?tag=3Dbraipick-20&mc_cid=
=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) (public library (http://www.worldcat.org=
/title/orlando-a-biography/oclc/297407&referer=3Dbrief_results?mc_cid=3D51=
73218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) ) =E2=80=94 a novel that=2C despite being a w=
ork of fiction (or=2C rather=2C a masterwork of fiction)=2C brims with exq=
uisitely articulated psychological truth about such perplexities as the el=
asticity of time
(https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/05/04/virginia-woolf-orlando-time/?mc_=
cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) and our propensity for self-doubt in=
 creative work (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/02/25/virginia-woolf-wr=
iting-self-doubt/?mc_cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) . (Vita Sackvill=
e-West =E2=80=94 Woolf=E2=80=99s lover and muse=2C who inspired Orlando (h=
ttps://www.brainpickings.org/2013/10/11/virginia-woolf-orlando-lesbian-rea=
dings/?mc_cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =E2=80=94 captured the well=
spring of this wisdom perfectly in recounting her very first encounter wit=
h Virginia (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/07/28/virginia-woolf-vita-s=
ackville-west/?mc_cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) : =E2=80=9CShe is b=
oth detached and human=2C silent till she wants to say something=2C and th=
en says it supremely well.=E2=80=9D)

http://www.amazon.com/Orlando-Biography-Virginia-Woolf/dp/015670160X/?tag=
=3Dbraipick-20&mc_cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

Woolf writes:

Vain trifles as they seem=2C clothes have=2C they say=2C more important of=
fices than merely to keep us warm. They change our view of the world and t=
he world=E2=80=99s view of us=E2=80=A6 There is much to support the view t=
hat it is clothes that wear us and not we them; we may make them take the=
 mould of arm or breast=2C but they mould our hearts=2C our brains=2C our=
 tongues to their liking.

Curiously=2C Woolf herself was of questionable sartorial sensibility =E2=
=80=94 so much so that even Vita noticed it from the midst of her infatuat=
ion=2C remarking on Virginia=E2=80=99s aesthetically atrocious choice of=
 =E2=80=9Cwoollen orange stockings [and] pumps.=E2=80=9D (https://www.bra=
inpickings.org/2016/07/28/virginia-woolf-vita-sackville-west/?mc_cid=3D517=
3218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) But perhaps Woolf was simply more interested i=
n the symbolic dimension of clothes than in the stylistic; more keen to ex=
plore that symbolism in her writing than in her wardrobe.

Tilda Swinton as Orlando

With an eye to her protagonist=E2=80=99s fluid transition between the male=
 and female genders =E2=80=94 one that happened in the novel by magic rath=
er than by medicine=2C for Woolf was writing two years before the first su=
ccessful gender reassignment surgery was completed=2C decades before the t=
erm =E2=80=9Ctransgender=E2=80=9D was coined=2C and nearly half a century=
 before Jan Morris=E2=80=99s trailblazing account of what it=E2=80=99s act=
ually like to change bodily genders (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/06=
/30/jan-morris-conundrum/?mc_cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =E2=80=
=94 Woolf considers the role of clothing as a vehicle of the transition an=
d a signifier of the fluidity of identity:

Clothes are but a symbol of something hid deep beneath. It was a change in=
 Orlando herself that dictated her choice of a woman=E2=80=99s dress and o=
f a woman=E2=80=99s sex. And perhaps in this she was only expressing rathe=
r more openly than usual =E2=80=94 openness indeed was the soul of her nat=
ure =E2=80=94 something that happens to most people without being thus pla=
inly expressed.

Fleshing out the ideas that would ripen a year later into her elegant case=
 for why the most creatively fertile mind is the androgynous mind (https:/=
/www.brainpickings.org/2015/04/15/virginia-woolf-androgynous-mind/?mc_cid=
=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C Woolf adds:

Different though the sexes are=2C they intermix. In every human being a va=
cillation from one sex to the other takes place=2C and often it is only th=
e clothes that keep the male or female likeness=2C while underneath the se=
x is the very opposite of what it is above.

Complement this particular passage of the wholly magnificent Orlando (http=
://www.amazon.com/Orlando-A-Biography-Virginia-Woolf/dp/015670160X/?tag=3D=
braipick-20&mc_cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) with Quentin Bell =E2=
=80=94 Woolf=E2=80=99s beloved nephew=2C collaborator in quirk (https://ww=
w.brainpickings.org/2013/06/24/charleston-bulletin-supplements-virginia-wo=
olf-quentin-bell/?mc_cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C and official=
 biographer =E2=80=94 on the morality of clothing (https://www.brainpickin=
gs.org/2013/09/06/quentin-bell-on-human-finery/?mc_cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=
=3D[UNIQID]) =2C then revisit Woolf on the relationship between lonelines=
s and creativity (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/06/16/virginia-woolf-=
loneliness/?mc_cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C how to live more f=
ully in the present (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/10/05/virginia-woo=
lf-past-present-moments-of-being/?mc_cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])=
 =2C and the epiphany that taught her what it means to be an artist (https=
://www.brainpickings.org/2015/09/09/virginia-woolf-cotton-wool-moments-of-=
being/?mc_cid=3D5173218563&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) .


